        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The main goal of this proposal is to observe the CN 6-5 hyperfine structure lines and the CO 6-5 line towards T Tau N. 

Spectral setup (basebands and spectral resolution):
--------------------------------------------------
The targeted lines will be observed simultaneously in band 9 by using two basebands:

- baseband (1) centered at 680.1 GHz to cover the CN 6-5 J=11/2-9/2 and J=13/2-11/2 hyperfine lines at 680.047 and 680.264 GHz. According to our disk model the CN 6-5 lines originate from the same disk region as the CN 5-4 lines, hence they will have comparable width (~ 7 km/s) and peak separation (~ 2.2 km/s) (see Figs. 1 and 2). We request a spectral resolution of 244.141 kHz (0.1 km/s), which will allow us resolving the line profile and peak separation. Note that the hyperfine structure of the CN 6-5 lines is not impeding to probe the disk kinematics, as the separation between the three brightest lines of the CN 6-5 J=11/2-9/2 and J=13/2-11/2 components is &lt;0.2 km/s, hence will not be resolved.
The bandwidth of 468.750 MHz (207 km/s) is perfectly suited to simultaneously cover also the fainter lines of the CN 6-5 J=11/2-9/2 and J=13/2-11/2 hyperfine structure.

- baseband (2) centered at 691.473 GHz to cover the CO 6-5 line. 
Also for the CO 6-5 line we request a spectral resolution of 244.141 kHz (0.1 km/s), thus obtaining a bandwidth of 203 km/s. This setting will allow us to cover the line high-velocity wings (velocity up to 30 km/s from systemic is detected in the CO 10-9 line) and to search for velocity asymmetries across the jet width down to 0.1 km/s.

Finally, we request to observe in a third baseband, baseband (3), centered at 693 GHz with the lowest spectral resolution (13.5 km/s) to cover the whole 2 GHz band and obtain a measurement of the continuum emission.

Spatial resolution:
------------------
We request the C34-3 configuration to obtain an angular resolution of 0.21" in band 9 which allows us to resolve the disk of T Tau N and the molecular jet width (according to our model the disk radius is of 100 AU, i.e. 0.7" at a distance of 140 pc, while atomic and molecular jet studies indicate a jet width of &lt;=200 AU). On the other hand the maximum recoverable scale of 2.8" is appropriate to cover the whole disk and the base of the jet up to a distance of about 400 AU from its driving source.

Requested sensitivity and total integration time:
------------------------------------------------
Our ProDiMo disk model of T Tau N perfectly reproduces the fluxes and profiles of the CN 5-4 lines observed with Herschel/HIFI and predicts  CN 6-5 J=11/2-9/2 and J=13/2-11/2 line fluxes of about 1.5e-18 W/m2 with a peak intensity of 20 Jy (see Fig. 2).
If the disk extends up to 100 AU (0.7"), as indicated by our model consistently with continuum mm maps and SED fitting, this translates into an intensity of 1.8 Jy per 0.21" beam. 
To detect the CN 6-5 line emission with a signal-to-noise of 10 (i.e. 0.18 Jy/beam sensitivity) after smoothing the spectrum to ~0.2 km/s (still sufficient to resolve the line profile, see Fig. 2), we request 4.93 minutes on-source integration time. This implies 37.39 minutes of total observing time, including calibrations and overheads.
As shown in Fig. 1 the CO 10-9 high-velocity emission is bright (Tmb~0.1-0.5 K in the 18" Herschel beam for velocities higher than 10 km/s with respect to systemic). Assuming a typical jet width of 100 AU and considering that the CO 6-5 line is expected to be at least a factor 2 brighter than CO 10-9 (by comparing with observations by Schuster et al. 1993 and from simple RADEX calculations for typical gas density and temperature) this translates into an intensity of ~1 Jy per 0.21" ALMA beam. Thus, as for the CN lines, the CO 6-5 high-velocity emission will be observed with a signal-to-noise of ~10. The 10 times brighter and more compact CO low-velocity emission probing the envelope and swept-up material will be observed with signal-to-noise &gt;=100.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
