    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The role of the ubiquitous jets in shaping the structure and evolution of protoplanetary disks is not well understood. This is due to the small angular scales involved and to the fact that most jet-active sources are still embedded in their parental envelope.
Interestingly, Herschel/HIFI observations of the T Tauri star (TTS) T Tau N indicate that high-J CN lines are a confusion-free probe of its disk, while CO 10-9 show extremely high-velocity gas expected to trace the molecular jet.
We propose to use ALMA to obtain for the first time a resolved map of the gas disk and of the molecular jet of T Tau N in the CN 6-5 680.0, 680.3 GHz and the CO 6-5 691.473 GHz.
This will allow us to:
1) verify the disk origin of high-J CN and to derive the disk size, inclination, and rotation by using our disk modeling code ProDiMo;
2) obtain the highest resolution image ever made of a TTS molecular-jet in the CO 6-5 line and derive the jet properties (width, velocity, rotation, mass/angular momentum transport);
3) test the validity of magneto-centrifugal models and constrain the jet launch region in the disk.
The derived disk-jet properties will allow investigating the jet's feedback on the disk.</prp:abstract>
